{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"ed319da9-cbbc-44a8-b74f-b7620c1d3a72","content":"Here's what I found:\n\n**`my_app/views.py:3`** — `datetime.now()`\nThis is a hardcoded static call, making the view difficult to test because you can't control the time value.\n\n### Recommended fix\n\nUse Django's `timezone.now()` with [`freezegun`](https://github.com/spulec/freezegun) or `unittest.mock.patch`, or inject the clock as a dependency:\n\n```python\nfrom django.utils import timezone\n\ndef index(request, clock=timezone.now):\n    now = clock()\n    return render(request, 'index.html', {'time': now})\n```\n\nThis way tests can pass a lambda or fixed value:\n\n```python\ndef test_index(self):\n    fixed = datetime(2026, 1, 1)\n    response = index(request, clock=lambda: fixed)\n```\n\nThis was a small project — only **1 file / 1 occurrence** found. No other untestable statics (`date.today()`, `uuid.uuid4()`, `random.*`, `os.environ`, etc.) were detected.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"bf8e2148-f02d-4712-bb63-f1809d86e2b8","outputTokens":263,"requestId":"083E:2D9C3A:5639E3:652E63:69EAD3DF"},"id":"5e7ef15c-2b86-45d2-9b7b-fd1c0b0dd863","timestamp":"2026-04-24T02:22:31.150Z","parentId":"5bdb5c25-b48d-468a-a023-8887196de2b1"}
